{"id":5986,"date":"2015-05-28T07:00:17","date_gmt":"2015-05-28T13:00:17","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/?p=5986"},"modified":"2019-02-06T11:00:30","modified_gmt":"2019-02-06T18:00:30","slug":"diy-driftwood-planter-succulents","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/diy-driftwood-planter-succulents\/","title":{"rendered":"DIY Driftwood Planter Filled with Succulents"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><div class=\"fusion-fullwidth fullwidth-box fusion-builder-row-1 nonhundred-percent-fullwidth non-hundred-percent-height-scrolling\" style=\"background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0);background-position: center center;background-repeat: no-repeat;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;margin-bottom: 0px;margin-top: 0px;border-width: 0px 0px 0px 0px;border-color:#eae9e9;border-style:solid;\" ><div class=\"fusion-builder-row fusion-row\"><div class=\"fusion-layout-column fusion_builder_column fusion-builder-column-0 fusion_builder_column_1_1 1_1 fusion-one-full fusion-column-first fusion-column-last\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-column-wrapper fusion-flex-column-wrapper-legacy\" style=\"background-position:left top;background-repeat:no-repeat;-webkit-background-size:cover;-moz-background-size:cover;-o-background-size:cover;background-size:cover;padding: 0px 0px 0px 0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-text fusion-text-1\"><p><em>With this step by step tutorial you'll easily be able to create a stunning piece of driftwood decor filled with succulents for your home. You only need a few supplies!<\/em><\/p>\n<p>A few months ago my Grandma was on a hike with some of our family. She found this beautiful piece of wood and thought it would look great filled with succulents! My uncle carried it back to their home and my grandma gave me a call. Of course I also thought it would look fabulous filled with succulents! I knew I wanted this to be an outdoor piece so that it stayed looking great all year long. So, I made sure to use only cold hardy succulents that would tolerate our cold winters.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5990 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Succulents-look-fantastic-in-this-piece-of-driftwood-decor-Learn-how-to-make-your-own-planter.jpg\" alt=\"Succulents look fantastic in this piece of driftwood decor! Learn how to make your own planter!\" width=\"735\" height=\"1102\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Succulents-look-fantastic-in-this-piece-of-driftwood-decor-Learn-how-to-make-your-own-planter-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Succulents-look-fantastic-in-this-piece-of-driftwood-decor-Learn-how-to-make-your-own-planter-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Succulents-look-fantastic-in-this-piece-of-driftwood-decor-Learn-how-to-make-your-own-planter.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>I don't know that this is technically driftwood since it was found in the desert, but it definitely has the same look. But, if you're looking to make your own succulent filled driftwood planter, here's what you'll need:<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.awin1.com\/cread.php?awinaffid=233213&awinmid=6220&clickref=driftwood_driftwood&p=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.etsy.com%2Fshop%2FCTSairplants%3Fsection_id%3D10084510%26ref%3Dshopsection_leftnav_9\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">Driftwood<\/a><\/li>\n<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.amazon.com\/gp\/product\/B004N5JF9U\/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=B004N5JF9U&linkCode=as2&tag=cassituttlpho-20&linkId=HW54JO2OK2BW2QBI\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">Floral Glue<\/a><\/li>\n<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.awin1.com\/cread.php?awinaffid=233213&awinmid=6220&clickref=driftwood_sphagnum&p=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.etsy.com%2Flisting%2F167620757%2Fmoss-for-wreath-making-floral-projects%3Fga_order%3Dmost_relevant%26ga_search_type%3Dall%26ga_view_type%3Dgallery%26ga_search_query%3Dsphagnum%2520moss%26ref%3Dsr_gallery_14\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">Sphagnum moss<\/a><\/li>\n<li style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.awin1.com\/cread.php?awinaffid=233213&awinmid=6220&clickref=driftwood_succulents&p=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.etsy.com%2Fshop%2FCTSairplants%2Fsearch%3Fsearch_query%3Dsempervivum%26order%3Ddate_desc%26view_type%3Dgallery%26ref%3Dshop_search\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">Succulents<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>Driftwood pieces come in a variety of shapes and sizes. Find a piece that fits in the space you plan to display it, or find one that matches your style and figure out where it'll go later :). The piece my Grandma found had a large\u00a0opening down the center that made it perfect for planting. Look for something with holes you can put succulents in, or just glue the succulents on top.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-6003 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Plant-succulents-in-a-piece-of-driftwood.jpg\" alt=\"Plant succulents in a piece of driftwood!\" width=\"735\" height=\"490\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Plant-succulents-in-a-piece-of-driftwood-500x333.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Plant-succulents-in-a-piece-of-driftwood-700x467.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Plant-succulents-in-a-piece-of-driftwood.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<h3>Use Floral Glue to Attach Moss<\/h3>\n<p>While succulents can grow without any soil, I want this piece to last for as long as possible so I decided to use sphagnum moss as a sort of soil to keep the succulents in place. In order to prevent everything from falling out, I made a line of floral glue in the back of the planter and attached the sphagnum moss to it.<\/p>\n<p>You may remember from my <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/living-succulent-earrings-and-ring\/\">succulent earrings<\/a> post that I highly recommend the <a href=\"https:\/\/www.amazon.com\/gp\/product\/B004N5JF9U\/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=B004N5JF9U&linkCode=as2&tag=cassituttlpho-20&linkId=HW54JO2OK2BW2QBI\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">Oasis floral glue<\/a>. This is a project that would do just fine with hot glue, but I find that the floral glue is becoming my favorite glue since it dries quickly and has a tighter hold that hot glue. After adding glue to the inside, I covered the entire length of the driftwood opening with moss.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5995 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Use-floral-glue-to-attach-moss-to-your-driftwood-planter.jpg\" alt=\"Use floral glue to attach moss to your driftwood planter\" width=\"735\" height=\"490\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Use-floral-glue-to-attach-moss-to-your-driftwood-planter-500x333.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Use-floral-glue-to-attach-moss-to-your-driftwood-planter-700x467.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Use-floral-glue-to-attach-moss-to-your-driftwood-planter.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5996 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Add-succulents-to-your-driftwood-planter-using-floral-glue-as-needed.jpg\" alt=\"Add succulents to your driftwood planter using floral glue as needed\" width=\"735\" height=\"490\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Add-succulents-to-your-driftwood-planter-using-floral-glue-as-needed-500x333.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Add-succulents-to-your-driftwood-planter-using-floral-glue-as-needed-700x467.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Add-succulents-to-your-driftwood-planter-using-floral-glue-as-needed.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<h3>Fill in with Succulents<\/h3>\n<p>Once you have the moss in, start adding succulents! I don't plan to hang this up right away (although I do plan to hang it) so I didn't glue in most of the succulents. There were a few that I couldn't quite keep in place so I used the floral glue to attach those. I packed the succulents in really tight. While I do want the planter to grow and overflow eventually, I'd like for the succulents to establish a really good root system and maintain this look for a little while. Planting them close together will help accomplish this.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5996 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Add-succulents-to-your-driftwood-planter-using-floral-glue-as-needed.jpg\" alt=\"Add succulents to your driftwood planter using floral glue as needed\" width=\"735\" height=\"490\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Add-succulents-to-your-driftwood-planter-using-floral-glue-as-needed-500x333.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Add-succulents-to-your-driftwood-planter-using-floral-glue-as-needed-700x467.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Add-succulents-to-your-driftwood-planter-using-floral-glue-as-needed.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-6002 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Pack-the-succulents-in-tightly-to-your-driftwood-planter.jpg\" alt=\"Pack the succulents in tightly to your driftwood planter\" width=\"735\" height=\"490\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Pack-the-succulents-in-tightly-to-your-driftwood-planter-500x333.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Pack-the-succulents-in-tightly-to-your-driftwood-planter-700x467.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Pack-the-succulents-in-tightly-to-your-driftwood-planter.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<h3>Water Later<\/h3>\n<p>After you have the succulents situated just right you're done! You won't want to water the planter right away. Give the roots a day or two to heal. After that you'll want to really soak the planter to help encourage the succulents to establish their roots. You may have to pour water over over the planter several times for the sphagnum moss to start absorbing it. Since there isn't a lot of moss or depth to a planter like this it will need to be watered a little more frequently than most of your arrangements.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-6001 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Learn-how-you-can-make-your-own-stunning-driftwood-planter-filled-with-succulents.jpg\" alt=\"Learn how you can make your own stunning driftwood planter filled with succulents\" width=\"735\" height=\"1102\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Learn-how-you-can-make-your-own-stunning-driftwood-planter-filled-with-succulents-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Learn-how-you-can-make-your-own-stunning-driftwood-planter-filled-with-succulents-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Learn-how-you-can-make-your-own-stunning-driftwood-planter-filled-with-succulents.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-6000 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Learn-how-to-make-a-driftwood-planter-filled-with-succulents.jpg\" alt=\"Learn how to make a driftwood planter filled with succulents\" width=\"735\" height=\"490\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Learn-how-to-make-a-driftwood-planter-filled-with-succulents-500x333.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Learn-how-to-make-a-driftwood-planter-filled-with-succulents-700x467.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Learn-how-to-make-a-driftwood-planter-filled-with-succulents.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5998 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Find-out-how-to-fill-a-driftwood-planter-with-cold-hardy-succulents.jpg\" alt=\"Find out how to fill a driftwood planter with cold hardy succulents\" width=\"735\" height=\"1102\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Find-out-how-to-fill-a-driftwood-planter-with-cold-hardy-succulents-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Find-out-how-to-fill-a-driftwood-planter-with-cold-hardy-succulents-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Find-out-how-to-fill-a-driftwood-planter-with-cold-hardy-succulents.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>This driftwood planter is my favorite project that I have done to date. I love that it will survive here year round and I'm really happy with the variety of cold hardy succulents I was able to find. The little bits of yellow throughout give it some visual interest and break up the reds and greens. I'm so excited to see how it changes as it grows and fills in even more! Thanks again to my grandma for finding this beautiful piece for me to plant succulents in!<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5992 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/This-driftwood-filled-with-succulents-is-so-beautiful.jpg\" alt=\"This driftwood filled with succulents is so beautiful!\" width=\"735\" height=\"1102\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/This-driftwood-filled-with-succulents-is-so-beautiful-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/This-driftwood-filled-with-succulents-is-so-beautiful-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/This-driftwood-filled-with-succulents-is-so-beautiful.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5994 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Use-cold-hardy-succulents-to-fill-a-beautiful-driftwood-planter.jpg\" alt=\"Use cold hardy succulents to fill a beautiful driftwood planter\" width=\"735\" height=\"1102\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Use-cold-hardy-succulents-to-fill-a-beautiful-driftwood-planter-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Use-cold-hardy-succulents-to-fill-a-beautiful-driftwood-planter-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/05\/Use-cold-hardy-succulents-to-fill-a-beautiful-driftwood-planter.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<\/div><div class=\"fusion-clearfix\"><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><div class=\"fusion-fullwidth fullwidth-box fusion-builder-row-2 nonhundred-percent-fullwidth non-hundred-percent-height-scrolling\" style=\"background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0);background-position: center center;background-repeat: no-repeat;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;margin-bottom: 0px;margin-top: 0px;border-width: 0px 0px 0px 0px;border-color:#eae9e9;border-style:solid;\" ><div class=\"fusion-builder-row fusion-row\"><div class=\"fusion-layout-column fusion_builder_column fusion-builder-column-1 fusion_builder_column_1_1 1_1 fusion-one-full fusion-column-first fusion-column-last\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-column-wrapper fusion-flex-column-wrapper-legacy\" style=\"background-position:left top;background-repeat:no-repeat;-webkit-background-size:cover;-moz-background-size:cover;-o-background-size:cover;background-size:cover;padding: 0px 0px 0px 0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-text fusion-text-2\"><p><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">.<\/span><\/p>\n<\/div><div class=\"fusion-clearfix\"><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"","protected":false},"author":7,"featured_media":8870,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":[],"categories":[1,69],"tags":[81],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/5986"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/7"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=5986"}],"version-history":[{"count":0,"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\